## STEP 4: Frontend Architecture

### 4.1 — Technology Stack

- Tailwind CSS (already loaded — do not re-import)
- CSS Grid for macro layout
- Vanilla JavaScript (ES6+) — no additional framework needed
- Dark mode: `bg-gray-900` base, `bg-gray-800/50` surface, `border-gray-700/30` borders
- Accent colours: green (#10b981) for approved/active, amber (#f59e0b) for edit/warning,
  red (#ef4444) for reject/error, blue (#3b82f6) for info

### 4.2 — State Management

Maintain a single `window.SPARK_STATE` object:

```javascript
window.SPARK_STATE = {
  job_id: null,
  channel_id: null,
  phase1_response: null,      // original LLM response — never mutated
  phase1_edited: {},          // user edits keyed by field path
  pipeline_step: 'idle',      // idle | running | awaiting_approval | dispatched
  edit_mode_active: false,
  export_format: 'md',
  export_sections: {
    market_research: true,
    titles: true,
    thumbnails: true,
    script: true,
    asset_manifest: true,
    seo_metadata: true,
    raw_metadata: false
  }
}
```

On "Approve & Dispatch": merge `phase1_response` with `phase1_edited` (edited values
take priority) and POST the merged object to the dispatch endpoint.

### 4.3 — Field Edit Tracking

Every editable field must have a `data-field-path` attribute matching its JSON path:

```html
<textarea data-field-path="section_2_title_strategy.variants[0].title">
  Inside the macroeconomics global finance crypto trends 2026 War
</textarea>
```

On every `input` or `change` event, write to `SPARK_STATE.phase1_edited[fieldPath]`.
On dispatch, read all edited values and overlay onto the original response.

